e Sydney Morning Herald]]|publication-place=Sydney|p=2|date=19 January 1933}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"itsanhonour\">{{cite web|url=https://honours.pmc.gov.au/honours/awards/1107389|website=Australian Honours Search|title=Mrs Zara Baer ARONSON}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"obe-smh\">{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17245266|title=Birthday Honours|date=24 June 1936|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publication-place=Sydney|p=14}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"herbrewstandard-tearooms\">{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article120268909|department=Australian Literature|title=Mrs. Zara Aronson, O.B.E.|date=2 July 1936|work=[[The Hebrew Standard of Australasia]]|publication-place=Sydney|p=4}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"sww-history\">{{cite web|website=Society of Women Writers NSW Inc.|url=https://womenwritersnsw.org/history/|title=SWW History|accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"sww-retirement\">{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17769238|title=Society of Women Writers|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publication-place=Sydney|date=17 October 1941|p=5}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"smh-death-article\">{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17912168|title=Mrs. Z. Aronson Dead|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publication-place=Sydney|date=3 July 1944|p=4}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"hebrew-standard-obit\">{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article120616707|title=Obituary|date=6 July 1944|publisher=[[The Hebrew Standard of Australasia]]|publication-place=Sydney|p=5}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"consecration\">{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article120615968 |title=Consecration of Tombstones|date=17 May 1945|publisher=[[The Hebrew Standard of Australasia]]|publication-place=Sydney|p=3}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aronson, Zara}}\n[[Category:1864 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian women writers]]\n[[Category:Australian Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Australian Jews]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian journalist  (1864-1944)}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Zara Aronson\n| image         = Zara Aronson in later life.png\n| caption       = Aronson in later life\n| birth_name    = Zara Baar\n| other_names   = {{plainlist|\n* Mrs. Fred Anderson\n* \"Thalia\" ([[pen-name]])}}\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|width=100%|country=AUS|OBE}}\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1864|09|04}}\n| birth_place   = Sydney, Australia\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1944|07|01|1864|09|04}}}\n| death_place   = at home, [[Darling Point]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n| resting_place = Jewish section of [[Rookwood Cemetery]]\n| occupation    = {{plainlist|\n* journalist\n* editor\n* welfare worker\n* restaurateur}}\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Frederick Aronson|{{date|1882-10-25}}|1928|end=d.}}\n}}\n\n'''Zara Baar Aronson''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|OBE}} ({{nee|Baar}}; 1864&ndash;1944) was a Sydney-based [[journalist]], [[editor]], [[welfare worker]], [[feminist]] and [[restaurateur]] of Jewish background. She was born in Australia but spent her formative years in Europe, before returning to Sydney where she became a lively socialite, as well as a social columnist and journalist in a number of major newspapers across Australian cities. She proved to be a tireless worker who pursued social and charity work as well as her own businesses in publishing, food and catering. Aronson's love for writing was evident and she helped form the [[Society for Women Writers]] and a local branch of the [[John O'London's Literary Circle]]. She was also the founder of the [[National Council of Women]]. Noted for her domestic skills in the kitchen, she raising significant funds for the Junior [[Red Cross]] during the outbreak of [[World War I]] by selling a cookery book, after which she published another successful cookbook, ''Twentieth Century Cookery Practice''. In later life she was made a civil officer of the [[Order of the British Empire]] for her services to the community.\n\n==Early life==\nAronson was born in Sydney to Moritz Baar, merchant of [[Hanover]] and London, and his wife Zillah, n\u00e9e Valentine. Her family moved to Europe when she was three years old, and she was initially educated at [[Bradford Girls' Grammar School]] in [[Yorkshire, England|Yorkshire]], England, then at [[Wiesbaden]] in Germany.<ref name=\"tabletalk\"/> Her family returned to Sydney in 1879 and, according to the ''[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]]'' \"attended Mrs Morell's school\".<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/><!-- I honestly tried to track this school down! -->\n\n==Early career and endeavours==\nShe was a member of the committees of the Sydney Industrial Blind Institution,<ref name=\"daily-telegraph-blind-institution\"/> the Thirlmere Home Committee and the Queen Victoria homes for consumptives.<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/><ref name=\"tabletalk\"/> She was also founder of the [[National Council of Women]], which was formed in 1896, and was its corresponding secretary from 1900 to 1901 and honorary secretary from 1906 to 1908.<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/><ref name=\"tabletalk\"/> After being encouraged to do so by Lucy, wife of [[Henry Gullett (New South Wales politician)|Henry Gullett]], she secured work as a contributor to the ''[[Australian Town and Country Journal]]'' and the ''[[Illustrated London News]]''.<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/><ref name=\"tabletalk\"/> From between 1897 and 1901 she also wrote for the ''[[Sydney Mail]]'' as a women's columnist under the name \"Thalia\".<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/><ref name=\"thalia\"/> From 1894 to 1899 she wrote the column \"Sydney Boudoir Gossip\" under the pen-name \"Zara\" for ''[[The Maitland Daily Mercury]]''.<ref name=\"ByZara\"/><ref name=\"truth-zara\"/>\n\n==Marriage and early career==\n[[File:Zara Baar Andorson.png|thumb|Aronson posing at her desk in 1901 for ''[[Table Talk (magazine)|Table Talk]]'' magazine.<ref name=\"tabletalk\"/>]]\nShe was married to Frederick Aronson on 25 October 1882 at the [[Great Synagogue (Sydney)|Great Synagogue]] at [[Elizabeth Street, Sydney]] by Rabbi A. B. Davis.<ref name=\"marriage\"/> The couple had a baby on 5 September 1883, but the baby died 13 days later.<ref name=\"baby-death\"/> The couple had a daughter Zelma and, in 1889, Aronson gave birth to a younger son, Malcolm Phillip.<ref name=\"son-geni\"/><ref name=\"obit-fred-aronson-smh\"/><ref name=\"the-sun-zelina-macphail-daughter\"/><ref name=\"funeral-notice-fred-aronson-argus\"/>\n\nLike Zara's father, her husband Frederick Aronson was also a merchant, having in 1899 established a wholesale jewellery and importing business, ''Frederick Aronson & Co.'' The Aronsons lived at 8 Lancaster Villas, Ocean Street in [[Woollahra]]<ref name=\"baby-death\"/> until 1901, before they moved to [[Melbourne]] as her husband took over the Melbourne branch of his company.\n\nShe returned to Sydney and from between 1903 and 1904 she worked on the monthly magazine ''The Home Queen'', where&mdash;according to the ''Australian Dictionary of Biography''&mdash;she was the editor but, along with the wife of [[Bernhard Ringrose Wise]], \"wrote much of it herself, including the theatrical and fashion columns\".<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/> It was whilst she was in this endeavour she found herself in conflict with [[Miles Franklin]] over a past column she wrote as Thalia. In a September 1902 column \"Thalia\" consistently misspelled Franklin's surname as \"Francklin\" and wrote that that \"her personal appearance is very much against her, as she is short, insignificant looking, and has a square face implying very little character until you begin to know her\" and that \"she certainly does not dress to the best advantage, which is also against her, as she has practically no idea on the subject of attractiveness\", however she praised her intelligence and education.<ref name=\"thalia-on-miles-franklin\"/>\n\nAronson evidently later wrote to Franklin, whose brother responded with what appears to have caused Aronson great offense as she wrote that \"although I quite believe that your sister has asked you to reply to her correspondence, I think that someone in your household might have taught you a little politeness to a lady editress\" and that \"I feel that Miss Franklin does not know that you have written me such a cheeky letter, as I always considered her a friend of mine\", though she did enquire as to which column Thalia wrote that gave offence.<ref name=\"aronson-to-franklin\"/> Franklin's response has not been preserved for history, however Aronson's response was \"The paragraph in question was shown to me and really I could not see anything very insolent in it. Certainly the Black <s>Heart</s> hair was a mistake, but then a little error like that is surely not worthy of your annoyance.\"<ref name=\"aronson-to-franklin\"/>\n\n==Later years and death==\nIn later years she was fashion editor for the ''[[Australian Town and Country Journal]]'' and the ''[[The Sunday Times (Sydney)|Sunday Times]]'', as well as the Sydney social correspondent for the ''[[Telegraph (Brisbane)|Telegraph]]''.<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/> After her husband setup a branch of his business in [[Perth]], [[Western Australia]] she moved with him and became a journalist for the ''[[Western Mail (Western Australia)|Western Mail]]''.<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/> Upon return to Sydney in 1914 she moved to 86 Darling Point Road, [[Darling Point]].<ref name=\"darling-point-death\"/> She assisted the Junior [[Red Cross]] in their efforts to support troops fighting in [[World War I]] by donating the proceeds of her cookery book, which raised more than \u00a3500.<ref name=\"smh-honours\"/> Her son, Malcolm, joined the military as a Motor Transport Driver in the [[Army Medical Corps]] and departed to fight in the First World War on 20 August 1916 on [[HMAT Shropshire]].<ref name=\"awm\"/>\n\nIn 1917, Aronson produced a well-received cookery book ''XXth Century Cooking and Home Decoration'' as Thalia,<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/><ref name=\"xxc-cookery-book\"/> and by 1918 she had started the Mary Elizabeth Tea Rooms at 60 [[King Street, Sydney]]. Her husband Frederick died in 1928.<ref name=\"frederck-aronson-funeral-notice\"/> She continued to run the Mary Elizabeth Team Rooms, which ''[[The Hebrew Standard of Australasia]]'' described as \"the meeting-place of many of Sydney's [[Bohemianism|Bohemian]] personalities\",<ref name=\"herbrewstandard-tearooms\"/> however in 1932 she declared bankruptcy through Hungerford, Spooner & Co. and eventually paid her creditors.<ref name=\"smh-bankruptcy\"/><ref name=\"smh-bankruptcy-first-dividend\"/><ref name=\"smh-bankruptcy-second-final-dividend\"/> During this time she also helped form the [[Society of Women Writers]], becoming the society's Honorary Secretary when it commenced in September 1925.<ref name=\"sww-history\"/><ref name=\"austdictbio\"/> She later became its president and retired on 17 October 1941, succeeded by Nora Kelly.<ref name=\"sww-retirement\"/> She was also a founder of the local branch of the [[John O'London's Literary Circle]].<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/>\n\nOn 23 June 1936 Aronson was made a civil imperial officer in the [[Order of the British Empire]] (OBE).<ref name=\"itsanhonour\"/><ref name=\"obe-smh\"/>\n\nAronson died at her house at Darling Point on 1 July 1944.<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/><ref name=\"smh-death-article\"/><ref name=\"hebrew-standard-obit\"/> She was buried in the Jewish section of [[Rookwood Cemetery]]<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/> and her memorial was consecrated on 20 May 1945.<ref name=\"consecration\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"austdictbio\">{{citation|author-link=Martha Rutledge|first=Martha|last=Rutledge|title=Allan, Aronson, Zara (1864\u20131944)|work=[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]]|publisher=National Centre of Biography, [[Australian National University]]|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/aronson-zara-5059|year=1993|volume=13}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"obit-fred-aronson-smh\">{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article16515585|title=Mr. F. Aronson|department=Obituaries|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publication-place=Sydney|date=11 December 1928}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"funeral-notice-fred-aronson-argus\">{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3976439|title=Mr. F. Aronson|department=Family Notices|work=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]]|publication-place=Melbourne|date=22 December 1928}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"daily-telegraph-blind-institution\">{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article236024451|title=Social|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publication-place=Sydney|date=12 August 1893|quote=We give a full list of the members of the committee :\u2014 His Excellency the Governor and Lady Duff (patrons), Mrs. Bow (unreadable)-Smith, Lady Manning, Lady Salomon, Miss Stephen, Mrs. W. P. Manning, Professor Anderson Stuart, Mrs. Curnow, Mrs. Airey, Mrs. Prendergast, Mrs. John Hay, Mrs.. John Tooliey, Mrs. Walter Hall, Mrs. Louis Haigh, Mrs.. Flood, Mrs. H. Gullett. Mrs. Fischer, Mrs.. George Cohen, Mrs. F. Drew, Mrs. J. Dean, Mrs. E. Ellis, Mrs. C. Edwards, Mrs. G. IT. Greene, Mrs. C. Metcalf, Mrs. Makinson, Mrs. Shewen, Mrs. W. Broomfield, Miss Ada Bell, Miss Barber, Miss Ben-susan, Misses Curnow, Miss F. Carter, Miss N. Church, Miss Dean, Miss Friend, Miss Fancett, Mrs. George Harris, Miss Huntley, Miss Hill, Misses Hill, Miss Jennings, Miss Lyons, Miss Marks, Misses M'Crae, Miss Phillips, Miss Roberts, Miss Thorne, Miss Watson; acting hon. secretaries, Zara Aronson, Gertrude Fischer.}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"tabletalk\">{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article146597254|title=Mrs. Zara Baar Aronson|work=[[Table Talk (magazine)|Table Talk]]|publication-place=Melbourne|date=5 September 19